thread_name: RE: Another Bad Day on Capital Metro (Wed., Feb. 10, 2021)
subject: Another Bad Day on Capital Metro (Wed., Feb. 10, 2021)
content: EXTERNAL E-MAILHello, again, Tangee Mobley:My time is valuable to me and I am a busy person.  Composing these e-mails to Capital Metro consumes even more of my limited time.Yesterday (Wednesday, February 10, 2021--BEFORE the weather turned bad in the Austin area), I was onboard a NORTHBOUND Route 300 bus.  The vehicle number of the bus was 2628 and, according to the overhead display, the Operator's ID was 311090.At approximately 3:45 pm, the driver parked the bus near the McDonald's restaurant located at 303 East Oltorf Street and, empty-handed, she entered the restaurant.  She emerged at 3:53 pm with a bag having a McDonald's logo on it and with a beverage cup likewise bearing the McDonald's logo.  I have no way of knowing if her entry into the restaurant was also for the purpose of using a restroom to which, of course, a bus driver is entitled.  She resumed driving the bus after keeping us waiting for several minutes.I did happen to notice that she consumed food while paused for a red light before crossing over Parker Lane.  She did the same at a red light before crossing over the next intersection at Burleson Road.  I also happened to notice her drinking the beverage while the bus was actually in motion while northbound on Springdale Road after crossing over East Martin Luther King, Jr. Boulevard and I noticed again that--while the bus in fact was in motion--she again drank from the beverage while northbound on Cameron Road while approaching East 52nd Street.It may be that Capital Metro is OK with all of this but I will tell you that from the viewpoint of a passenger, these "optics" are not good.  If this conduct is NOT in compliance with Capital Metro policy, then please consider this as my formal complaint against this driver and a review of the video from the bus would be encouraged.Just when I thought that things could not go down-hill any further, Capital Metro proved me wrong.A bit later that same day, I boarded a NORTHBOUND Route 383 bus (Vehicle number 2565 and, according to the overhead display, Operator ID 305830) which departed the North Lamar Transit Center at 5:30 pm.When the bus arrived on northbound Burnet Road, just south of Longhorn Boulevard at approximately 5:40 pm (at the bus stop labeled "Rutland"station), the driver suddenly parked and then exited from the bus.She struck up a conversation with a man who was standing near the bus stop and then got on her cell phone to make a call.  At first, this angered me.  However, she later told those of us onboard that this was the location at which there was to be a switch of drivers as she, herself, would be re-assigned to a different route at that point.We sat there on vehicle 2565 and waited and waited and waited.  She then told us that we would have to resume our travel on the next-scheduled Route 383 bus.  At 6:09 pm--having waited for a half hour--the next-scheduled Route 383 bus (vehicle 2512) did arrive and all of us exited vehicle 2565 in order to board vehicle 2512.  This was a significant delay for me in getting to my destination and it does not reflect well upon Capital Metro to have this level of disorder in its administrative functions.The average Austinite has a choice in the matter because--unlike me--the average Austinite has access to a vehicle.  Pandemic--or no pandemic--these examples from yesterday show why the average Austinite will not bother to use public transportation (and relieve traffic congestion on Austin's notoriously-busy roadways) as there are so many examples of difficulty and poor-quality service in what should be the simple task of getting people from Point A to Point B in timely fashion.A reply would be much-appreciated.Thank you,GREGORY WATSONThursday, February 11, 2021

thread_name: Re: Another Bad Day on Capital Metro (Wed., Feb. 10, 2021)
subject: Another Bad Day on Capital Metro (Wed., Feb. 10, 2021)
content: EXTERNAL E-MAILHello, again, Tangee Mobley:My time is valuable to me and I am a busy person. Composing these e-mails to Capital Metro consumes even more of my limited time.Yesterday (Wednesday, February 10, 2021--BEFORE the weather turned bad in the Austin area), I was onboard a NORTHBOUND Route 300 bus. The vehicle number of the bus was 2628 and, according to the overhead display, the Operator's ID was 311090.At approximately 3:45 pm, the driver parked the bus near the McDonald's restaurant located at 303 East Oltorf Street and, empty-handed, she entered the restaurant. She emerged at 3:53 pm with a bag having a McDonald's logo on it and with a beverage cup likewisebearing the McDonald's logo. I have no way of knowing if her entry into the restaurant was also for the purpose of using a restroom to which, of course, a bus driver is entitled. She resumed driving the bus after keeping us waiting for several minutes.I did happen to notice that she consumed food while paused for a red light before crossing over Parker Lane. She did the same at a red light before crossing over the next intersection at Burleson Road. I also happened to notice her drinking the beverage whilethe bus was actually in motion while northbound on Springdale Road after crossing over East Martin Luther King, Jr. Boulevard and I noticed again that--while the bus in fact was in motion--she again drank from the beverage while northbound on Cameron Roadwhile approaching East 52nd Street.It may be that Capital Metro is OK with all of this but I will tell you that from the viewpoint of a passenger, these "optics" are not good. If this conduct is NOT in compliance with Capital Metro policy, then please consider this as my formal complaint againstthis driver and a review of the video from the bus would be encouraged.Just when I thought that things could not go down-hill any further, Capital Metro proved me wrong.A bit later that same day, I boarded a NORTHBOUND Route 383 bus (Vehicle number 2565 and, according to the overhead display, Operator ID 305830) which departed the North Lamar Transit Center at 5:30 pm.When the bus arrived on northbound Burnet Road, just south of Longhorn Boulevard at approximately 5:40 pm (at the bus stop labeled "Rutland"station), the driver suddenly parked and then exited from the bus.She struck up a conversation with a man who was standing near the bus stop and then got on her cell phone to make a call. At first, this angered me. However, she later told those of us onboard that this was the location at which there was to be a switch ofdrivers as she, herself, would be re-assigned to a different route at that point.We sat there on vehicle 2565 and waited and waited and waited. She then told us that we would have to resume our travel on the next-scheduled Route 383 bus. At 6:09 pm--having waited for a half hour--the next-scheduled Route 383 bus (vehicle 2512) did arriveand all of us exited vehicle 2565 in order to board vehicle 2512. This was a significant delay for me in getting to my destination and it does not reflect well upon Capital Metro to have this level of disorder in its administrative functions.The average Austinite has a choice in the matter because--unlike me--the average Austinite has access to a vehicle. Pandemic--or no pandemic--these examples from yesterday show why the average Austinite will not bother to use public transportation (and relievetraffic congestion on Austin's notoriously-busy roadways) as there are so many examples of difficulty and poor-quality service in what should be the simple task of getting people from Point A to Point B in timely fashion.A reply would be much-appreciated.Thank you,GREGORY WATSONThursday, February 11, 2021

Log out of the device
Wait a minute and log back in
Tap the three horizontal line menu in the left-hand corner of the screen

Tap the icon to the right of the ticket to save it to the device

thread_name: FW: Another Bad Day on Capital Metro (Wed., Feb. 10, 2021)
subject: FW: Another Bad Day on Capital Metro (Wed., Feb. 10, 2021)
content:
Please log this complaint into the system.
Thanks,
Tangee Mobley Vice President Bus Operations and Maintenance
Capital Metropolitan Transportation Authority
Email: tangee.mobley@capmetro.org
2910 East 5th  Street, Austin, TX 78702
-----Original Message-----
From: Gregory Watson https://urldefense.proofpoint.com/v2/url?u=http-3A__gregory.watson.austex-40gmail.com&d=DwIGaQ&c=euGZstcaTDllvimEN8b7jXrwqOf-v5A_CdpgnVfiiMM&r=V_YbMZjQBNNLkAPyIG-mvBp8_5RDN4UDNlUUePI-mVHvDHDAYA51j2ML-cElzg0L&m=_RDFX8TlxGYF2PC-rqs6Ly6_0VXQgMuOF4nhWpapg3I&s=_ciEGo1xnFmD7cxWuroun_MHFMiy4CO7n5yKHmwr6Qw&e=
Sent: Thursday, February 11, 2021 11:31 PM
To: Mobley, Tangee https://urldefense.proofpoint.com/v2/url?u=http-3A__Tangee.Mobley-40capmetro.org&d=DwIGaQ&c=euGZstcaTDllvimEN8b7jXrwqOf-v5A_CdpgnVfiiMM&r=V_YbMZjQBNNLkAPyIG-mvBp8_5RDN4UDNlUUePI-mVHvDHDAYA51j2ML-cElzg0L&m=_RDFX8TlxGYF2PC-rqs6Ly6_0VXQgMuOF4nhWpapg3I&s=FxJRL2A8Me0aJU63rMFJYDNhP-onrARnqSFQ6t-LSmo&e=
Subject: Another Bad Day on Capital Metro (Wed., Feb. 10, 2021)
EXTERNAL E-MAIL
Hello, again, Tangee Mobley:
My time is valuable to me and I am a busy person.  Composing these e-mails to Capital Metro consumes even more of my limited time.
Yesterday (Wednesday, February 10, 2021--BEFORE the weather turned bad in the Austin area), I was onboard a NORTHBOUND Route 300 bus.  The vehicle number of the bus was 2628 and, according to the overhead display, the Operator's ID was 311090.
At approximately 3:45 pm, the driver parked the bus near the McDonald's restaurant located at 303 East Oltorf Street and, empty-handed, she entered the restaurant.  She emerged at 3:53 pm with a bag having a McDonald's logo on it and with a beverage cup likewise bearing the McDonald's logo.  I have no way of knowing if her entry into the restaurant was also for the purpose of using a restroom to which, of course, a bus driver is entitled.  She resumed driving the bus after keeping us waiting for several minutes.
I did happen to notice that she consumed food while paused for a red light before crossing over Parker Lane.  She did the same at a red light before crossing over the next intersection at Burleson Road.  I also happened to notice her drinking the beverage while the bus was actually in motion while northbound on Springdale Road after crossing over East Martin Luther King, Jr. Boulevard and I noticed again that--while the bus in fact was in motion--she again drank from the beverage while northbound on Cameron Road while approaching East 52nd Street.
It may be that Capital Metro is OK with all of this but I will tell you that from the viewpoint of a passenger, these "optics" are not good.  If this conduct is NOT in compliance with Capital Metro policy, then please consider this as my formal complaint against this driver and a review of the video from the bus would be encouraged.
Just when I thought that things could not go down-hill any further, Capital Metro proved me wrong.
A bit later that same day, I boarded a NORTHBOUND Route 383 bus (Vehicle number 2565 and, according to the overhead display, Operator ID 305830) which departed the North Lamar Transit Center at 5:30 pm.
When the bus arrived on northbound Burnet Road, just south of Longhorn Boulevard at approximately 5:40 pm (at the bus stop labeled "Rutland"
station), the driver suddenly parked and then exited from the bus.
She struck up a conversation with a man who was standing near the bus stop and then got on her cell phone to make a call.  At first, this angered me.  However, she later told those of us onboard that this was the location at which there was to be a switch of drivers as she, herself, would be re-assigned to a different route at that point.
We sat there on vehicle 2565 and waited and waited and waited.  She then told us that we would have to resume our travel on the next-scheduled Route 383 bus.  At 6:09 pm--having waited for a half hour--the next-scheduled Route 383 bus (vehicle 2512) did arrive and all of us exited vehicle 2565 in order to board vehicle 2512.  This was a significant delay for me in getting to my destination and it does not reflect well upon Capital Metro to have this level of disorder in its administrative functions.
The average Austinite has a choice in the matter because--unlike me--the average Austinite has access to a vehicle.  Pandemic--or no pandemic--these examples from yesterday show why the average Austinite will not bother to use public transportation (and relieve traffic congestion on Austin's notoriously-busy roadways) as there are so many examples of difficulty and poor-quality service in what should be the simple task of getting people from Point A to Point B in timely fashion.
A reply would be much-appreciated.
Thank you,
GREGORY WATSON
Thursday, February 11, 2021

content:
Jordan Bursonjordanburson00@gmail.comApp Name: Capital MetroApp Version : 4.31.2 1057OS Version : 10
Okay first of all I bought a 31 day bus pass Order CM3422313-705 on 1/12/21. I didn't active it until 1/16/21. Today your app was malfunctioning and running really slow and sometimes not loading my prepaid ticket when I was trying to ride the bus. My 31 day pass was good until 2/17/21. So I tried uninstalling the app and reinstalling the app and when I opened it again my 31 day pass was gone. I know I signed into the same account the 31 day pass was on and it wasn't there. I had a lot of things going on today and it didn't help that it was like 32 degrees outside, I tried calling your customer service line and the operator was somewhat helpful but he didn't resolve the issue. So then I tried buying just one $1.25 single ride bus pass and your app didn't let me buy one on my account with the username jordanburson00@gmail.com. I tried twice and it
didn't work. So I switched to another username gulfstream812@gmail.com and put in my card information to verify that it is really me and finally was able to purchase the ticket. So all I received was one $1.25 single ride ticket in the account with the username gulfstream812@gmail.com. I finally got home and looked at the statements from both cards I used which with only one I was able to buy one 1.25 bus pass. You charged me twice in my card ending with 3164 and once with my card ending in 1926 and I only received one $1.25 bus pass. You can look it up on my account. I wasn't able to answer the phone call when your operator tried calling me back, like I said it was 32 degrees outside and I was just trying to get inside someplace. Please write me back and check on the orders and details I presented to you here and let me know what you are going to do to resolve this issue. I have experienced minor problems in the past using your app but never anything like this. My phone number is 512-202-7457 or you can email me back at this email address. Please respond as soon as you can. Thank you.

subject: Re: Cold Weather Shelters Activated
content:
If the person in the electric wheelchair is stranded outside and/or is at risk First responders should be called.Electric Wheelchairs are typically used for those that can not use a manual wheelchair. Electric wheelchairs have a manual release lever so that someone can push them in an emergency. Cold weather is bad for any batteries.As I predicted, in a previous email, Cap Metro will deny transportation to destinations and cold weather shelters (CWS) due to the weather.

In this case the paratransit service denied service
based on weather and (a disability if the regular buses are still running). The paratransit system must still run as long as the main bus route runs to give people with disabilities equal access to CWS that can not use the regular buses. The main bus routes will also shut down due to weather.Additionally, They should extend their 1/4 mile limits from the nearest bus routes or bus stops to ensure people with a disability can get access to transportation,
especially in a disaster
area or state of emergency. They need to be door to door service.The Governor
has declared a state of emergency due to the weather and the pandemic.Due to travel barriers, People need to be able to remotely register for CWS from any location and get a hotel in their immediate area for the duration of the CW declarations, preferably
a hotel that has food service and willing to service
meals and that is accessible without having to travel outside the building as it may become impassable.Question, do first responders have spiked tires for icy

Good Evening Amber,We have food covered for today. We have also sent over shelf stable meals just in case roads are closed. I will keep you posted if assistance is needed during this CWS activation.Thank you,MichelleGetOutlook for iOSOutlook-xk0qrjnd.png
Good morning,Please see updated Cold Weather Shelter flyerattached.Kindly,-Lara

﻿Good morning,This e-mail is to notify you that Cold Weather Shelters will be activated tonight. The average overnight low temperature for tonight is27 degrees F and wet.The City of Austin, Travis County, and community partners have activated cold weather shelters since yesterday evening. Moving forward, cold weather shelters will beoperating 24 hours a day for along as conditions dictate. Individuals in sheltering this evening will be offered the opportunity to remain during the day and the upcoming nights. Those seeking shelter tonight willstill be able to go to the Central Library at 6 p.m. to be transported to shelters. Families with children may arrive at Downtown Salvation Army Shelter located at 501 E. 8th Street by 6pm. Clients with pets will not be turned away. Pets will receive accommodationthrough Animal Services. Please reach out if you need additional information.A warming center will be open beginning today, Feb. 13 located at the Palmer Events Center. The warming center will open at 10 a.m. Individuals in the warming centers will be eligible to be transported to sheltersin the evening on request.Predicted weather for the next three days is as follows: Cold weather shelters and the warming center are activated each day. If you’d like more information, the Cold Weather Shelter hotline is 512-305-ICEE (4233).Sunday, February 14Monday, February 15Tuesday, February 16Avg. content: Jordan Bursonjordanburson00@gmail.comApp Name: Capital MetroApp Version : 4.31.2 1057OS Version : 10Okay first of all I bought a 31 day bus pass Order CM3422313-705 on 1/12/21. I didn't active it until 1/16/21. Today your app was malfunctioning and running really slow and sometimesnot loading my prepaid ticket when I was trying to ride the bus. My 31 day pass was good until 2/17/21. So I tried uninstalling the app and reinstalling the app and when I opened it again my 31 day pass was gone. I know I signed into the same account the 31day pass was on and it wasn't there. I had a lot of things going on today and it didn't help that it was like 32 degrees outside, I tried calling your customer service line and the operator was somewhat helpful but he didn't resolve the issue. So then I triedbuying just one $1.25 single ride bus pass and your app didn't let me buy one on my account with the usernamejordanburson00@gmail.com. I tried twice and itdidn't work. So I switched to another usernamegulfstream812@gmail.com and put in my card information to verify that it is really me and finally was able to purchase the ticket. So all I received was one $1.25 single ride ticket in the accountwith the username gulfstream812@gmail.com. I finally got home and looked at the statements from both cards I used which with only one I was able to buy one 1.25 bus pass. You charged me twice inmy card ending with 3164 and once with my card ending in 1926 and I only received one $1.25 bus pass. You can look it up on my account. I wasn't able to answer the phone call when your operator tried calling me back, like I said it was 32 degrees outside andI was just trying to get inside someplace. Please write me back and check on the orders and details I presented to you here and let me know what you are going to do to resolve this issue. I have experienced minor problems in the past using your app but neveranything like this. My phone number is 512-202-7457 or you can email me back at this email address. Please respond as soon as you can. Thank you.
That is wonderful! I have also credited a Local Day pass to your account for you to use at your convenience for the day you were unable to access your pass.Sondra Williams

content: We apologize for the inconvenience this has caused you.If you are still having this issue please attempt the following steps, and contact us if it does not help.Have you tried signing out of the app and then signing back in? Try the following steps.·Log out of the device·Wait a minute and log back in·Tap the three horizontal line menu in the left-hand corner of the screen·Tap More·Tap Ticket Storage; the ticket should show saved to the cloud·Tap the icon to the right of the ticket to save it to the deviceThank you,John Torres
